  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent and detect money laundering, which typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Screening customers against watchlists\n- Understanding customer business activities\n\n2. Reporting Requirements\n- Submitting Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Filing Currency Transaction Reports (CTRs)\n- Reporting transactions above certain monetary thresholds\n\n3. Transaction Monitoring\n- Tracking and analyzing financial transactions\n- Identifying unusual or suspicious patterns\n- Maintaining detailed transaction records\n\n4. Risk Assessment\n- Developing comprehensive anti-money laundering (AML) programs\n- Conducting periodic risk evaluations\n- Implementing appropriate internal controls\n\n5. Staff Training\n- Educating employees about money laundering risks\n- Training on detection and reporting procedures\n- Ensuring compliance with regulations\n\n6. Record Keeping\n- Maintaining transaction documentation\n- Preserving customer identification records\n- Retaining records for specified periods\n\nThese obligations are typically enforced by regulations like the Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) in the United States and similar laws internationally, with potential significant penalties for non-compliance.",
